### Implementing Askama Template Rendering (Rust)

Source: https://github.com/askama-rs/askama/blob/master/book/src/introduction.md

Defines a Rust struct `HelloTemplate` using the `#[derive(Template)]` macro to link it to the `hello.html` template. The struct field `name` provides the context for the template's variable. The `main` function demonstrates instantiating the struct and rendering the template to stdout.

```Rust
use askama::Template; // bring trait in scope

#[derive(Template)] // this will generate the code...
#[template(path = "hello.html")] // using the template in this path, relative
                                 // to the `templates` dir in the crate root
struct HelloTemplate<'a> { // the name of the struct can be anything
    name: &'a str, // the field name should match the variable name
                   // in your template
}

fn main() {
    let hello = HelloTemplate { name: "world" }; // instantiate your struct
    println!("{}", hello.render().unwrap()); // then render it.
}
```

--------------------------------

### Implementing Custom Error Response - Axum - Rust

Source: https://github.com/askama-rs/askama/blob/master/book/src/frameworks.md

This Rust boilerplate demonstrates creating a custom `AppError` type compatible with Axum, designed for handling Askama rendering errors. It includes deriving `Debug`, `Display`, and `Error`, and implementing the `axum::response::IntoResponse` trait. This implementation converts the error into an HTTP response, setting the status code and rendering a dedicated error template (`error.html`) or a default message as the body.

```Rust
use axum::response::IntoResponse;
use askama::Template;

#[derive(Debug, displaydoc::Display, thiserror::Error)]
enum AppError {
    /// could not render template
    Render(#[from] askama::Error),
}

impl IntoResponse for AppError {
    fn into_response(self) -> Response {
        #[derive(Debug, Template)]
        #[template(path = "error.html")]
        struct Tmpl { … }

        let status = match &self {
            AppError::Render(_) => StatusCode::INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR,
        };
        let tmpl = Tmpl { … };
        if let Ok(body) = tmpl.render() {
            (status, Html(body)).into_response()
        } else {
            (status, "Something went wrong").into_response()
        }
    }
}
```

--------------------------------

### Returning Template Output - Axum Handler - Rust

Source: https://github.com/askama-rs/askama/blob/master/book/src/frameworks.md

This Rust code snippet illustrates how to return the output of a rendered Askama template from an Axum handler function. It demonstrates wrapping the `String` result of `template.render()` within `axum::response::Html` to ensure it's sent with the correct `Content-Type`. The handler returns a `Result` with a custom `AppError` type.

```Rust
use axum::response::{Html, IntoResponse};

async fn handler() -> Result<impl IntoResponse, AppError> {
    …
    Ok(Html(template.render()?))
}
```

--------------------------------

### Define and Render Askama Template Rust

Source: https://github.com/askama-rs/askama/blob/master/askama/README.md

Illustrates the Rust code needed to use the Askama template engine. It defines a struct (`HelloTemplate`) with a field matching the template variable, derives the `Template` trait, specifies the template file path, instantiates the struct with data, and renders the template to standard output using `hello.render().unwrap()`. This requires the `askama::Template` trait to be in scope.

```Rust
use askama::Template; // bring trait in scope

#[derive(Template)] // this will generate the code...
#[template(path = "hello.html")] // using the template in this path, relative
                                 // to the `templates` dir in the crate root
struct HelloTemplate<'a> { // the name of the struct can be anything
    name: &'a str, // the field name should match the variable name
                   // in your template
}

fn main() {
    let hello = HelloTemplate { name: "world" }; // instantiate your struct
    println!("{}", hello.render().unwrap()); // then render it.
}
```

--------------------------------

### Implementing Custom Error Response - Actix-Web - Rust

Source: https://github.com/askama-rs/askama/blob/master/book/src/frameworks.md

This Rust boilerplate code defines a custom `AppError` enum for Actix-Web applications using Askama. It shows how to derive necessary traits (`Debug`, `Display`, `Error`) and implement `actix_web::error::ResponseError` to define the HTTP status code and `actix_web::Responder` to generate an appropriate response body, typically by rendering an error template like `error.html`. Requires `askama`, `thiserror`, and `displaydoc`.

```Rust
use actix_web::{HttpResponse, Responder};
use actix_web::error::ResponseError;
use actix_web::http::StatusCode;
use actix_web::web::Html;
use askama::Template;

#[derive(Debug, displaydoc::Display, thiserror::Error)]
enum AppError {
    /// could not render template
    Render(#[from] askama::Error),
}

impl ResponseError for AppError {
    fn status_code(&self) -> StatusCode {
        match &self {
            AppError::Render(_) => StatusCode::INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR,
        }
    }
}

impl Responder for AppError {
    type Body = String;

    fn respond_to(self, req: &HttpRequest) -> HttpResponse<Self::Body> {
        #[derive(Debug, Template)]
        #[template(path = "error.html")]
        struct Tmpl { … }

        let tmpl = Tmpl { … };
        if let Ok(body) = tmpl.render() {
            (Html::new(body), self.status_code()).respond_to(req)
        } else {
            (String::new(), self.status_code()).respond_to(req)
        }
    }
}
```

